title: SI LA GENTILESSE ÉTAIT INTERDITE 😂
description: Mdrr en fait c’est pas un POV c’est la réalité 😂 Si vous voulez empêcher cette loi débile de passer, le lien est en bio ✨ En inondant sa boîte mail y’a moyen que ça passe pas ahah 🤞  Pour plus de détails sur cette loi : C’est une directive européenne qui menace de criminaliser tous ceux qui aideraient des personnes sans papiers, sous le prétexte de lutter contre le trafic. Donc on parle de la petite mamie qui distribue de la nourriture tous les dimanches, du médecin qui soigne, du sauvetage en mer, etc.  Ce qu’on demande c’est de modifier le texte pour ajouter au moins une clause d’exemption humanitaire, pour que les asso et ONG puissent continuer d’aider les personnes ayant besoin ! Sauf que @EPP bloque ce minimum du minimum. Il faut donc interpeller son vice-president @fxbellamy pour lui demander que son parti clarifie sa position. Merci d’avoir lu jusque là 🫶  Merci @benjerryfr (oui oui les glaces) d’avoir collaboré avec nous sur cette vidéo ❤️

title: Explosion Outside 💥☕ | Key Calmly Adds Sugar (Key & Peele S4E8 Fan Edit)
description: This video is a fan-made edit from Key & Peele Season 4, Episode 8, focusing on the legendary coffee moment where chaos erupts outside… and Key absolutely does not care 😆☕.  At first, he’s just trying to add sugar to his coffee. Then an explosion happens outside 💥. Sirens, panic, total destruction — and yet, Key remains completely calm, unfazed, and laser-focused on one thing: adding more sugar 🧂😂.  The comedy comes from the contrast. While the world seems to be falling apart, Key’s expression barely changes. No reaction. No panic. Just steady hands, quiet determination, and an endless commitment to perfecting his coffee 🤯👏.  Edited based on the original subtitles, this clip highlights the subtle timing, deadpan delivery, and escalating absurdity that make Key & Peele sketches so iconic. Sometimes the funniest reaction… is no reaction at all 😌🔥.  If you love understated comedy, ridiculous contrasts, and classic Key & Peele moments, this fan edit captures one of the most unforgettable scenes from Season 4 Episode 8.  ⚠️ Disclaimer  This video is a fan-made edit created for entertainment purposes only. title: MDR, la fin 💀💀 #humour #chocolatchaud #24heures #challenge #humoristefrancais #funny #comedy ￼
This Prisoners Scene Went Too Far 🔨
description: One of the most intense moments in Prisoners comes from the bathroom interrogation scene, where Hugh Jackman’s character completely loses control. To make the scene feel as real as possible, director Denis Villeneuve encouraged Jackman to push past comfort and explore the character’s desperation. The goal wasn’t just to show anger, but the terrifying mindset of a parent who believes he has nothing left to lose.  The scene was filmed over many hours, which added to the emotional exhaustion on set. At one point, Jackman improvised smashing the sink with a hammer, an action that wasn’t fully planned in the script. Because Paul Dano didn’t know exactly when or how far Jackman would go, his shocked and fearful reactions are genuine, not carefully performed beats.  That unpredictability is what gives the scene its raw power. You can feel the tension not only between the characters, but in the space itself. The violence feels messy, uncomfortable, and uncontrolled, which matches the moral collapse of Jackman’s character in that moment.  What makes the scene memorable isn’t just its brutality, but how grounded it feels. There’s no dramatic music cue or flashy editing to soften the impact. It’s a slow, suffocating confrontation where the audience is forced to sit with the consequences of desperation, making it one of the most disturbing and effective scenes in modern thrillers.  #Shorts #Movie #Movies

title: Elles doivent compléter les Expressions Françaises 🇫🇷😂
Academy Awards 2001, Ben Stiller turned a deliberate stage malfunction into an iconic live-TV moment
description: While presenting Best Makeup, a platform was meant to lift him fully onstage — but it stopped at chest height, leaving him awkwardly trapped. Instead of rushing or breaking the illusion, Stiller leaned into it, delivering his lines deadpan while physically embodying the idea that makeup is only meant to be seen from the neck up. The timing, restraint, and total commitment sold it as effortless comedy, and many viewers assumed it was an unscripted failure. It’s still remembered as one of the smartest examples of using a “malfunction” — real or staged — to elevate a joke rather than distract from it.

title: #movie The Sharp Cop’s Hunch | How A Cop Knew The Store Was Robbed Without Being
description: Ever seen a cop who can sense crime just by having a casual chat? In this scene from the heartwarming comedy "It Could Happen to You" (1994), starring Nicolas Cage, we see Charlie the police officer do just that. The film is famous for its story about a lottery ticket and an act of kindness, but this moment highlights Charlie's intuition and connection to his community in a different way.  Watch as Officer Charlie (Nicolas Cage) walks into a store, perhaps for his morning coffee, and strikes up a routine conversation with the owner. Nothing seems out of the ordinary at first. But through subtle cues—maybe a nervous glance, an item slightly out of place, or the shopkeeper's tone—Charlie pieces together that something is very wrong.
